column169: On June 11, 2024, four (4) 1-gallon pails of UN3264 were crushed in transit and released approximately 2.5-gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement below. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Restoration (ER) to remediate the impacted site. ER discovered that R+L personnel had placed four damaged drums into one (1) 15-gallon drum. ER personnel utilized a neutralizing agent to remediate the trailer. Granular absorbents were then placed on the impacted areas and swept using hand tools. ER then broke down the impacted pallet completing remediation. All spent absorbents as well as the pallet were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum. Both drums were staged onsite for future disposal.

column169: On 6/5/2024 at approximately 1900, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 4009660 at the ramp facility in Jamacia NY, reporting an undeclared battery shipment.  The shipment consisted of 4 cardboard containers wrapped in black shrinkwrap, each filled with used and damaged cell phones.  None of the packages were properly declared as UN3481 Lithium ion batteries contained in equipment Section I.  The  shipment was not prepared in accourdance with IATA Regulation. column169: On June 13, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of corrosive liquid had a faulty seam and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior and asphalt beneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. Crews deployed a neutralizing agent to the impacted areas and placed the damaged drum into a 95-gallon over-pack for disposal. TLE personnel applied granular absorbents to the impacted trailer floor and asphalt surface and worked them in with hand tools. All corrosive liquid impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 95-gallon drum and one (1) 35-gallon drum for disposal.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal LBY experienced a UN1789 Blue Whale Muriatic Acid pH Reducer release from multiple boxes each containing (2) 1-gallon poly jugs. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-gallon of product released to 1’ x 1’ area of the trailer floor and a 3’ x 3’ area of the concrete dock due to the jugs being crushed in transit. Sodium bicarbonate was deployed to clean and neutralize the impacted areas. A total of (20) 1-gallon jugs, impacted cardboard, and impacted absorbents were collected and containerized into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

RESPONDER USED DECISION TREE AND CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET TO CHECK FOR HAZARD RESPONSE PROCEEDURES. USED ZEP ZORB AND LINED SPILL TRAY TO TRANSPORT BOX TO DAMAGE CAGE FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

ONE AIR PACKAGE SHIPPING FROM NEW HARTFORD, NY TO SYRACUSE, NY BROKE OPEN REQUIRING A PACKAGE REWRAP. UPON INSPECTION A MC LEOD GAGE DEVICE CONTAINING MERCURY HAD BROKEN.  AN OUTSIDE RESPONSE TEAM WAS CONTACTED. THE OUTSIDE RESPONDER CONTAINED, CLEANED, AND REMOVED THE PACKAGE AND CONTENTS FROM THE FACILITY. NO EVACUATION OF THE FACILITY WAS NEEDED AND NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED. THE OUTSIDE RESPONDER ADVISED AN ESTIMATED FIVE POUNDS OF MERCURY WAS CONTAINED IN THE MC LEOD GAGE DEVICE WITH APPROXIMATELY 30 ML (1 OZ) OF MERCURY RELEASING. THERE WERE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER BOX. THE PACKAGE WAS OFFERED FOR AIR SERVICE BUT ONLY MOVED IN THE GROUND NETWORK PRIOR TO THE LEAKAGE. THIS PACKAGE  HAS NOT BEEN ACCEPTED FOR AIR OR TRANSPORTED IN THE AIR BY UNITED PARCEL SERVICE CO.

column169: On June 5, 2024, at 1455 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by CEVA Logistics personnel in Dallas, Texas regarding the release of IPA TT-I-735A.  Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of a total of 1 gallon of IPA TT-I-735A (UN1219, 3, II) from (3) 5-gallon steel pails. The release was caused by a load shift and contained to a 3ft x 3ft area on the trailer floor. Contractors were able to clean the release with absorbents and the proper PPE. The damaged pails containing residual material were placed in (1) 95-gallon overpack DF and the impacted absorbents were placed in (1) 55-gallon DF and taken offsite by contractors for proper disposal.

column169: SET  Environmental  was  dispatched  to  the  site. Upon  the  contractor’s  arrival,  personnel  observed  that the  released  material  impacted a  10ft-by-10ft area of  the  trailer  floor  and  5ft-by-14ft area of  the  asphalt  lot  and estimated that  eight  (8)  gallons  of material  was  released  due  to  load  shift  that  crushed  four  boxes  containing  eight  (8)  1-gallon  plastic jugs.  SET  Environmental  personnel  deployed  a  neutralizer  and  then  a  granular  absorbent  to  the impacted areas. The spent material was gathered and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon poly drums and the damaged plastic jugs were placed into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste  will  remain  onsite  for  Dayton  Freight’s  contracted  hazardous  waste  vendor  to  coordinate disposal.

column169: On June 13, 2024, one (1) 70-pound battery was punctured and released approximately 1.5-gallons od battery acid to the trailer interior. XPO Logistics terminal LSL experienced a UN2922 Santoflex 44PF  release from a 55-gallon metal drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 55-gallons of product released to a 20’ x 8' area of the trailer floor & a 30' x 10' area of the asphalt lot below due to a forklift puncture. The impacted areas were cleaned with a neutral soap solution and absorbents. The damaged drum was placed into a 95-gallon poly overpack. The impacted absorbents, cut up impacted pallets, and all impacted debris were collected and containerized into (13) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: AT THE UPS MIAMI FLORIDA FACILITY, NINE SKIDS MOVING TO COLOMBIA VIA UPS AIR CARGO SERVICE WERE FOUND CONTAINING BOXES WITH COVERED LITHIUM BATTERY MARKS. ALL NINE SKIDS ARE BLACK SHRINK WRAPPED WITHOUT ANY DANGEROUS GOODS INDICATORS ON THE OUTER COVERING. A TOTAL OF 23 BOXES EACH CONTAINING 72 WIRELESS LITHIUM-ION BATTERY POWERED MYJOY COOL EARBUDS WERE FOUND. DURING FORKLIFT MOVEMENT OF THE SKIDS, WE CAN SEE LITHIUM BATTERY MARKS UNDERNEATH ON THE VERY BOTTOM OF THE FREIGHT. THE AIR WAYBILL DOES NOT INDICATE LITHIUM BATTERIES ARE BEING SHIPPED TO COLOMBIA. THERE ARE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON ANY PART OF THE OUTER BLACK SHRINK WRAPPED FREIGHT. EHMA EXPRESS INC, 8509 NW 68TH ST, MIAMI FL 33166 IS THE ISSUING CARRIER'S AGENCY ON THE AIR WAYBILL. SHIPPER'S NAME AND ADDRESS IS SUNRISE FINANCIAL BUSINESS, S.A. C/O FIFO WIRELESS, INC, 10900 NW 21ST STREET SUITE 210, MIAMI FL 33172.

column169: On June 4, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of acetone was damaged and released approximately one-half (0.5) gallon of product to the trailer interior. FCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the acetone-impacted trailer and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum. column169: On June 7, 2024, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN2922 was punctured in transit and released approximately three (3) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Valley Environmental Response (VER) to remediate the impacted site.  VER deployed neutralizers to the trailer floor, surrounding cargo and collected one (1) 5-gallon plastic pail into one (1) 55-gallon double lined poly drum. VER utilized absorbent pads and neutralizer to the impacted cargo.  VER neutralized the wooden pallet, deconstructed it with hand tools, and placed it into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. Crews utilized hand tools to collect all spent absorbent pads, neutralizers, and containerized it into the same one (1) 55-gallon poly drum as the deconstructed pallet. VER staged onsite the two (2) 55-gallon poly drums of waste for further handling

column169: XPO Logistics terminal XDP experienced a UN1760 Step Down Low Odor Finish Liquidator release from a 5-gallon poly pail. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 5-gallons of product released to a 5’ x 5’ area of the trailer floor due to a load shift, causing the pallet to tip over. The impacted area was cleaned and neutralized with citric acid solution, baking soda, and absorbents. The damaged pail and all impacted cleanup debris were containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The remaining pails in the shipment were re-stacked and secured for continued transit. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage

column169: It was reported that approximately 2-gallons of Sodium Hydroxide Solution (UN1824) was released. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the dock floor at door #17. ERTS advised contractor HEPACO would respond due to the corrosive state of the product and amount released. HEPACO advised Oil Dri was applied to the impacted area and the concrete dock was neutralized with a muriatic acid solution. The damaged drum was then placed into a 95-gallon poly drum and the impacted absorbents, pads and PPE were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum for disposal. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release.

column169: On June 4, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN1760 was damaged by a forklift and released approximately twenty (20) gallons of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site.  FCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the UN1760-impacted dock floor and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum, the damaged drum of product was placed into one (1) 95-gallon overpack.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal UBU experienced a UN3352 Omni Brand Lambda 1 EC release from 36 boxes each containing (4) 1-gallon poly jugs. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of product released to the cardboard packaging only due to lose caps on all jugs. The jugs were poured into (3) 55-gallon poly drums to be disposed of as pure liquids. The jugs were then rinsed, and all rinse water was placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The impacted cardboard, empty poly jugs, and impacted pads were placed into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

It has been brought to our attention that a package was found to be leaking at the unload side. As a precautionary measure, the package was immediately placed in a hazardous bag and subsequently transferred to a red tote. The red tote was then transported to the Quality Assurance (QA) cage for further examination. Upon examination, it was discovered that the content had a loose cap, leading to a leakage that spread across the other bottles

While parked at a truck stop, the Veolia driver noticed a leak coming from the front of the trailer. The driver notified Veolia management personnel and applied oil dry to the material that released to the ground. Veolia employees investigated the spill and discovered the container had tipped over while in transportation and leaked from the drum closure. The spill was remediated, the drum was closed properly and the load was properly secured for continued transportation without any further incident.
column170: The employees that prepared this load for transportation were reminded to check all containers for proper closure prior to the loading a truck for shipment. In addition, they were advised on the importance of proper loading and securement of containers to prevent shifting during transportation.

column169: On June 14, 2024, at 0257 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Roadrunner  personnel in Livermore, California regarding the release of Unitex Melt Down Plus. Roadrunner terminal personnel discovered the release of 5 gallons of Unitex Melt Down Plus (UN1760 Corrosive Liquid, N.O.S(Ethanolamine) 8, II) from (1) 5-gallon plastic pail. The release was caused by a puncture and contained to an area inside the trailer. Terminal personnel were able to clean the release with absorbents and containerized the waste in (1) 55-gallon DF and staged it onsite for proper disposal.

On June 11, 2024, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN1760 had a faulty valve and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Resolute Environmental & Response Services, LLC (RERS) to remediate the site.  RERS closed the valve preventing any further leakage. RERS then wiped down all totes and deployed soda ash to the affected areas and swept them in using hand tools. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal.

column169: On June 13, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of printing ink was punctured by a forklift and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel deployed a degreasing agent and granular absorbents to the impacted trailer floor. The crew utilized hand tools to work material into the trailer floor. FCE patched the damaged drum and placed it into one (1) 85-gallon over pack. The crew collected the spent absorbents and debris into one (1) 55-gallon drum.

column169: DURING NORMAL HANDLING PROCESS AT THE UPS HONG KONG INTERNATIONAL CHEK LAP KOK FACILITY ONE AIR PACKAGE FROM HONG KONG DESTINED TO THE USA WAS OBSERVED SMOKING ON THE BELT. THE PACKAGE WAS IMMEDIATELY TAKEN AWAY FROM THE BELT AND PLACED IN A SEGREGATED AREA. THE SMOLDERING INCREASED AND SUBSEQUENTLY THE PACKAGE BEGAN BURNING. UPS STAFF USED A FIRE EXTINGUISHER TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE. THE EVENT WAS DISCOVERED PRIOR TO THE PACKAGE BEING LOADED INTO AN AIR CONTAINER. THE PACKAGE HAD PASSED A DANGEROUS GOODS ACCEPTANCE AUDIT PRIOR TO THE LITHIUM BATTERY INCIDENT. THE PACKAGE WAS FULLY DECLARED WITH AN APPROPRIATE IATA SHIPPERS DECLARATION AS UN3480 LITHIUM ION BATTERIES, SECTION IA OF PACKING INSTRUCTION 965. AFTER THE EVENT WAS EXTINGUISHED, THE OPERATIONS NOTED THE INNER THREE BATTERIES WERE NOT PROPERLY SEPARATED OR PROTECTED. ADDITIONALLY, NO WATT HOUR MARKINGS WERE FOUND ON THE BATTERIES.  PER 49CFR 171.15, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS CONTACTED BY TELEPHONE TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. THE OFFICER WAS UNABLE TO ACCEPT THE TELEPHONE REPORT DUE TO THE EVENT NOT OCCURRING IN THE USA.

column169: Hepaco  was  dispatched  to  the  site.  Upon  the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 6in-by-200ft area of the concrete  roadway  and  a  53’-by-8ft  area  of  the  trailer  floor  and  estimated  that  thirty  (30)  gallons  of material was released due to load shift that resulted in a puncture to one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. Various  cleanup  debris  and  spent absorbents were gathered and placed into four (4) additional 55-gallon poly drums. The damaged drum was over packed into one (1) 85-gallon poly drum still containing approximately twenty-five (25) gallons of product. The generated waste was left at the terminal in a secure location. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

column169: On 06/10/2024, this shipment had hidden dangerous goods that were discovered in this during the shipment inspection process at the at the DHL LGA Service Center, 230-19 Rockaway Blvd, Springfield Gardens, NY 11413 I   Transportation by road has been confirmed.

A Veolia employee noticed spillage outside of a Veolia straight truck parked in the 10-Day Facility lot around 9:00a., and reported the incident immediately. Employees immediately offloaded the truck to identify the drum that was releasing the material, to find that the suspect drum had imploded. There were no evident punctures or abrasions on the drum, so the suspected cause of the leakage is due to a faulty seam on the drum. The spill was cleaned up with oil dry and the drum was overpacked for continued transportation to the disposal facility.
column170: Employees have been reminded to fully assess the integrity of drums upon shipment.
